data.title: On the Waterfront
data.meta_description: Where to watch On the Waterfront (1954) starring Marlon Brando, Karl Malden, Lee J. Cobb and directed by Elia Kazan.
data.text:
New York Daily NewsKate Cameron

Kazan over-emphasized the last sequence in the film, but on the whole, his fine direction shows in the strength and power of the dramatic action on the screen.

indieWireBrandon Judell

But sometimes great art, like Wagner's and Celine's, comes from people you wouldn't want to break bread with. But snub the art? Who'd want to miss Marlon Brando's performance?

Boston GlobeMarjory Adams

On the Waterfront is strong, tough and cruelly violent, but it is also a film that should make theatre history for 1954. It will strike audiences with special impact because it is based on undisputed fact.

Chicago TribuneMae Tinee

The film has a ring of authenticity. It is as close to the unvarnished truth as has been seen on the screen in many a day and a shining example of intelligent use of a medium too seldom utilized to its greatest extent.

Philadelphia InquirerMildred Martin

If reservations still linger in any one's mind concerning Brando's ability as an actor, On the Water front should dispel them completely.

Detroit Free PressHelen Bower

This is a motion picture with a great deal to say, and a great deal will be said about it.

St. Louis Post-DispatchMyles Standish

[On the Waterfront] seethes with vitality and raw realism. It is an exciting, brilliant, electric job replete with remarkable acting. Certainly it is one of the year's top pictures.

Los Angeles TimesEdwin Schallert

Between the powerful beginning and finish On the Waterfront evolves through many highly suspenseful sequences that show the grip exerted by the labor boss, and the courageous resistance against his domination by Miss Le Saint.

Fort Worth Star-Telegram/DFW.comAnn Jones

For those who like their movies realistic, tender and sometimes brutal, this documentary of the docks is a masterful piece of film artistry.

Hollywood ReporterJack Moffitt

This brutal, violently realistic drama, set against the sordid background of the New York waterfront, packs a terrific wallop that results in topflight entertainment.

TIME MagazineTIME Staff

On the Waterfront has a script that is a work of love and shows it.

VarietyVariety Staff

Under Elia Kazan's direction, Marlon Brando puts on a spectacular show, giving a fascinating, multi-faceted performance as the uneducated dock walloper and former pug, who is basically a softie with a special affection for his rooftop covey of pigeons.

New YorkerPauline Kael

It is one of the most powerful American movies of the 50s, and few movies caused so much talk, excitement, and dissension -- largely because of Marlon Brando's performance as the inarticulate, instinctively alienated bum, Terry Malloy.

Boston GlobeTy Burr

So when does it hit you that you're in the presence of movie greatness?

Chicago ReaderJonathan Rosenbaum

It's hard to deny that Marlon Brando's performance as a dock worker and ex-fighter who finally decides to rat on his gangster brother (Rod Steiger) is pretty terrific.

Village VoiceJ. Hoberman

It is thanks to Brando that this posthumous Popular Front classic is a heart-clutcher from beginning to end.

RogerEbert.comWael Khairy

Even though there's not a single scene where sluggers dance around within the confines of a ring, Kazan's film is in fact a boxing film in disguise.
